219→const TASK_PROMPT = `
220→1 - Understand and write your understanding of every single and
221→each WORKFLOW AND CRITICAL statement.
222→2 - Understand and write your understanding of the work in progress
223→  described in progress.txt and compared with the actual files.
224→
225→WORKFLOW:
226→0. Understand Project
227→1. Read ./.claude/progress.txt and identify the most important pending task;
228→   - Specific task prioritization is indicated/tagged/prefixed with '[P'+number+']'
229→   - Tasks tagged with '[P0]' must be done before anything else.
230→   - Tasks tagged with P bigger than 999 (e.g. '[P1000]'), are low-priority
231→   tasks, they should be done when possible, but they must be done
232→   (they are not ignorable); If the task takes longer and there are other
233→   non-low-priority tasks, document progress and revert the status to "- [ ]".
234→
235→2. If NO pending tasks exist, plan next improvements, add tasks and stop
236→3. If there are tasks, mark it as IN_PROGRESS and then sequentially run:
237→   - Evaluate scope: if the task involves more than ~3 files or multiple concerns,
238→      break it into smaller sub-tasks in progress.txt BEFORE starting. Each sub-task
239→      must be completable in a single iteration (small, atomic, committable change).
240→   - Execute task
241→   - Run 'bun run check' and fix found issues.
242→   - Launch 1 review agents to deeply review the work, giving
243→      the entire context of the task, simulating pull request.
244→   - Review output and consider improvements
245→   - Implement corrections if needed
246→   - Update progress.txt marking task as completed
247→   - Commit task changes (not include unrelated code)
248→   - Output status block (see below)
249→   - Stop
250→
251→CONTEXT:
252→- The .loop/ directory contains archived progress logs and iteration logs.
253→- Files named <timestamp>-progress.txt contain previously completed tasks
254→  that were rotated out of progress.txt to keep context lean.
255→- You can read files in .loop/ if you need historical context about past work.
256→
257→CRITICAL:
258→- ALL tasks and instructions are deliberate.
259→- No task is optional.
260→- If more work is necessary, add a new task to the file, set "exit": false, and Stop
261→- Never remove tasks, unless to update status;
262→- Never include workarounds and add tasks to fix all you found ('as any' for example is a workaround)
263→- No task should be submitted as "look reasonable."
264→- Every task must be delivered with professional quality, without any makeshift solutions.
265→- For tasks with visual parts, full visual and interaction tests with Playwright MCP are required.
266→- Never consider any mistake or error to be expected or acceptable.- Never consider any mistake or error to be expected or acceptable.
267→- Never trust project comments or documentation without confirming on actual
268→code.
269→
270→--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
271→
272→OUTPUT STATUS (REQUIRED at end of EVERY response):
273→You MUST output this exact format at the END of your response:
274→
275→RALPH_STATUS: { "exit": <true if ALL tasks done, false otherwise>, "task": "<completed task name>", "remaining": <number of pending tasks> }
276→
277→Examples:
278→- Task completed but more remain: RALPH_STATUS: { "exit": false, "task": "Create usePoints hook", "remaining": 5 }
279→- ALL tasks completed: RALPH_STATUS: { "exit": true, "task": "Delete Redux files", "remaining": 0 }
280→
281→`;
